# Database changes (Prisma) — single strategy

This project uses **SQL migrations only** for any database that is (or will be) used with `prisma migrate deploy` (local dev Postgres, staging, production, Docker). **All agents must follow this; there is no alternate path.**

## Do this

| Situation | Command / action |
|-----------|------------------|
| You changed `prisma/schema.prisma` and want it in git + deployable | `yarn prisma migrate dev --name <short_snake_description>` against a **dev** database (or author `migration.sql` via `prisma migrate diff` if no DB). **Commit** the new folder under `prisma/migrations/`. |
| CI / production / fresh container | `yarn prisma migrate deploy` only. |
| Check drift | From an empty DB, `migrate deploy` then `prisma migrate diff` (or validate) so schema matches `schema.prisma`. |

## Do not do this

- **`prisma db push`** on **any** database that also uses **migrations** (including your own `movienightdb` if `_prisma_migrations` exists). `db push` skips migration history and causes duplicate objects, missing columns, and **P3009 / P3018** style failures.
- **Commit `schema.prisma` changes without a new migration** unless the user explicitly said **prototype / throwaway only** (and then do not run `migrate deploy` on shared DBs until a real migration exists).
- **`prisma migrate resolve`** (applied / rolled-back) **without understanding** the real DB state — that rewrites history and can lie about what ran. Use only when deliberately recovering from a documented failure.

## Agent workflow (checklist)

1. Edit `schema.prisma`.
2. Run **`migrate dev`** (preferred) to generate SQL, **or** generate diff and a migration file if no local DB.
3. Review generated `migration.sql`.
4. Commit **both** `schema.prisma` and `prisma/migrations/<timestamp>_*`.
5. Never suggest **`db push`** as the fix for schema drift on this project; suggest **`migrate deploy`** after migrations exist, or a **one-off recovery** plan if history and DB are broken.

## Why

Production and Docker expect **`prisma migrate deploy`**. One pipeline avoids “works on my machine” drift and the `WatchEntry.source`-style missing-column errors when code assumes migrated schema.

---

For humans: if a migration fails mid-run, stop, fix or roll back explicitly (`migrate resolve` + documented SQL), then continue — do not mix `db push` into that database.
